ati\n\n\nMantras may be practiced with motives =\r\nor without motives. With motives are *\nsa-kama*, lit. =93with desire=94 for=\r\n fruit and result. Without motives are *\nnish-kama*, =93without desire,=94 =\r\nonly to gain the purification leading to\nliberation.\n\n*Sa-kama* is of two k=\r\ninds (1) to fulfill a personal desire, such as: may my\nhusband=92s nature c=\r\nhange; may I grow rich, (2) a subtler kind is, I want to\nlive a life of pra=\r\nyer, worship [or service], but practical obstacles come\nin the way. =93I ca=\r\nnnot pray or serve because my husband won=92t let me as he\nbecomes jealous.=\r\n=94 To correct such situations, the practice is the same as\nthe first, but =\r\nwith an ultimate desire which is *nish-kama*. There the *\nsa-kama* desire i=\r\ns to pave the way for the *nish-kama* goal. Even the\ndesire for liberation =\r\nmay be dropped, and the mantra may be practised *\nguru-prity-artham*, for g=\r\nuru&#39;s satisfaction, to receive grace.\n\nThose that are done *sa-kama* may be=\r\n for specific purposes, such as to ward\noff or heal an illness, to prevent =\r\naccidents foretold, to prolong life, to\nalleviate financial problems, to ac=\r\nhieve a specific goal such as to be able\nto buy a house, or capture power, =\r\nor improve an organization, or regain\nfriendship, or eliminate someone&#39;s an=\r\nimosity towards oneself, and so forth.\n\nAnother subtle differentiation may =\r\nbe understood here. One may do such\nundertakings (a) for the purpose of sel=\r\nf-purification and liberation only,\nor (b) to obtain a desired result, or (=\r\n3) to attain the *siddhi*(s) of that\nmantra. The formula of =93number of sy=\r\nllables multiplied by hundred thousand\nplus twenty per cent=94 is definitel=\r\ny efficacious to achieve the *siddhi*,\nthat is to say, that one then has th=\r\ne powers inherent in the mantra and is\nable to use the mantra with just one=\r\n or three or such other minimum number\nof remembrances to attain a desired =\r\nresult for oneself or for one=92s\nstudents or seekers. (etc.)\n\n\n\nHope that =\r\nhelps!\n\nOn Tue, Jun 12, 2012 at 2:32 AM, rajarshi nandy &lt;rajarshi14@yahoo.c=\r\no.in&gt;wrote:\n\n&gt; **\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;  Dear Priyank,\n&gt;\n&gt; These three attitudes that you h=\r\nave named are for any sadhana, not just\n&gt; Tantra. Even so called Vedic Sadh=\r\nanas are often done for material gains.\n&gt; Recall how most of the Sanskrit s=\r\ntotras of various deities contain a\n&gt; phalastuti (the expected results), is=\r\n that not material gain? Doing a\n&gt; Mahamrityunjaya Mantra for health benefi=\r\nts, isn&#39;t that a material gain? It\n&gt; is not the path, but the attitude of t=\r\nhe sadhaka which determines for what\n&gt; he/she is performing a certain sadha=\r\nna.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; Yogis and/or those who do sadhana using &#39;Vedic&#39; tools also acquir=\r\ne\n&gt; siddhis. Yogis acquire siddhis, which can come as a byproduct of the pa=\r\nth.\n&gt; The problem is not with siddhis per se, it is with misusing them or\n&gt;=\r\n commercializing them or hanging on to them. Any sadhaka who can gain a\n&gt; s=\r\niddhi, can also let go of that siddhi whenever he/she wants.\n&gt;\n&gt; Speaking o=\r\nf Karma, everything has a karma of it&#39;s own. Tantra, as it\n&gt; stands today, =\r\nis roughly divided into two major geographic and\n&gt; philosophical demarcatio=\r\nns. The style practiced in South India - mostly\n&gt; Dakshina Margi - and that=\r\n practiced in Bengal and adjacent areas - mostly\n&gt; Vama Margi. In my person=\r\nal opinion, the adherents of the path in both\n&gt; cases, generally speaking, =\r\nhave been trapped in two delusions born out of\n&gt; collateral byproducts of t=\r\nheir respective paths. The first step of Shakti\n&gt; sadhana is generating sha=\r\nkti. Second step is holding the shakti. Third step\n&gt; is channeling the shak=\r\nti. In view of this, one school of Tantra that is\n&gt; prevalent today has tie=\r\nd itself up in too much of technicalities, such that\n&gt; on an average they f=\r\norget to capture shakti (here shakti means energy, not\n&gt; Shakti the supreme=\r\n Goddess). WHile the other school is able to generate and\n&gt; hold shakti muc=\r\nh better, only to commercialize the same and/or misuse it\n&gt; (generally spea=\r\nking, expcetions are there too). End result, both eventually\n&gt; do not end u=\r\np producing enough genuine Tantrik saints.\n&gt;\n&gt;  &lt;&lt;\n&gt; i am wondering &quot;if at =\r\nall&quot; and &quot;what kind&quot; of karmic liabilities one might\n&gt; be getting into ?&gt;&gt;\n=\r\n&gt;\n&gt; A fair exchange is never a robbery, as Vimalananda says. Theoretically,=\r\n\n&gt; when the *right person* performs many of the things mentioned in that bl=\r\nog,\n&gt; (and some of the stuff there is not exactly accurately portrayed), he=\r\n/she\n&gt; will know how to balance the karmic impact well. In the hands of an\n=\r\n&gt; immature individual, it can lead to disaster. Further, the so called\n&gt; di=\r\nvision between &#39;classical Tantra&#39; and &#39;folk Tantra&#39; is not as sharp and\n&gt; c=\r\nlear as it is made out there. Each influences the other and is very much\n&gt; =\r\nintermingled.  Every sadhana in Vama Margi Tantra has a firm spiritual\n&gt; ba=\r\nsis. Performed correctly, with the right attitude, and by the right\n&gt; indiv=\r\nidual, it leads to very high spiritual states.\n&gt;\n&gt; -Regards\n&gt;  Rajarshi\n&gt;\n&gt;=\r\n\n&gt;\n&gt; *\n&gt; Bazeecha-e-atfal hain duniya mere aage.\n&gt; Hota hain shab-o-roz tam=\r\nasha mere aage\n&gt;\n&gt;  Ek khel hain aurang-e-sulemaan mere nazdeek\n&gt; Ek baat h=\r\nain ijaz-e-masiah mere aage.\n&gt; *\n&gt;\n&gt;   ------------------------------\n&gt; *Fr=\r\nom:* priyank_priyank &lt;aks_day@...&gt;\n&gt; *To:* vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.c=\r\nom\n&gt; *Sent:* Tuesday, 12 June 2012 10:14 AM\n&gt; *Subject:* [vedic-wisdom] Kar=\r\nmic liability for Tantra &quot;materia